2026-06-24 20:36:09,476 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=e9413d83644f3307bfd9a848836a661f span=9460ec2ba414fdb7 parent=- | {'role': 'tool', 'parts': [{'type': 'tool_call_response', 'id': 'x8p1s5945', 'response': '{\n  "results": [\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "2.4",\n      "section": "2.4 Relationship Value",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0328,\n      "text": "## 2.4 Relationship Value\\n\\nFAB recognises that relationship profitability extends beyond the individual transaction. A relationship-adjusted pricing approach applies where a client demonstrates a material cross-sell contribution, measured as total annual revenue across all FAB products divided by total RWA. Relationship Value adjustments may reduce the required margin by up to 25 basis points from the standard floor, subject to:\\n\\n- Documented cross-sell revenues exceeding AED 500,000 per annum across the relationship.\\n- Approval by the relevant credit authority (see Section 5).\\n- Annual review of continued cross-sell performance.\\n\\n## 3. Minimum Pricing Floors by Product\\n\\nThe following tables set out the minimum all-in pricing floors applicable to each product category. These floors represent the absolute minimum below which no transaction may be executed without a formal Pricing Exception (Section 6). Floors are stated in basis points over the applicable FTP rate unless otherwise specified.\\n\\nNOTE: FTP rates are published monthly by FAB Treasury and are available on the internal Treasury portal. All floor rates in this section are stated as SPREADS over FTP. The total all-in rate must not fall below FTP + the stated floor spread.\\n\\n## 3.1 Corporate Term Loans\\n\\nTable 3.1 sets out minimum pricing floors for standard corporate term loans, segmented by client internal credit rating and facility tenor.\\n\\n| Client Rating   | Tenor ≤ 1 Year                                        | Tenor 1-3 Years   | Tenor 3-5 Years   | Tenor > 5 Years   | Notes                                          |\\n|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------|-------------------|-------------------|-------------------|------------------------------------------------|\\n| AAA / AA        | 65 bps                                                | 80 bps            | 100 bps           | 130 bps           | Investment grade sovereign or quasi- sovereign |\\n| A               | 85 bps                                                | 105 bps           | 130 bps           | 165 bps           | Strong investment grade corporate              |\\n| BBB             | 115 bps                                               | 145 bps           | 180 bps           | 220 bps           | Standard investment grade                      |\\n| BB              | 165 bps                                               | 210 bps           | 260 bps           | 320 bps           | Sub-investment grade / leveraged               |\\n| B               | 240 bps                                               | 300 bps           | 370 bps           | 450 bps           | Speculative / requires senior credit approval  |\\n| CCC and below   | Not permitted without Group Credit Committee approval |                   |                   |                   | See Section 6                                  |\\n\\nEXAMPLE: A BBB-rated client requesting a 4-year AED term loan. FTP for 4-year AED = 4.85% (as at June 2024). Minimum floor spread = 180 bps. Minimum all-in rate = 4.85% + 1.80% = 6.65%.\\n\\n## 3.2 Revolving Credit Facilities (RCFs)\\n\\nRevolving credit facilities are subject to the pricing floors in Table 3.2. Commitment fees on undrawn portions are in addition to the drawn margin and are not included in the floor calculations below.\\n\\n| Client Rating   | Drawn Margin Floor   | Commitment Fee Floor   | Facility Fee Floor   | Tenure ≤ 3 Years   | Tenure > 3 Years   |\\n|-----------------|----------------------|------------------------|----------------------|--------------------|--------------------|\\n| AAA / AA        | 60 bps               | 20 bps                 | 10 bps               | Applies            | Add 15 bps         |\\n| A               | 80 bps               | 25 bps                 | 12 bps               | Applies            | Add 20 bps         |\\n| BBB             | 110 bps              | 30 bps                 | 15 bps               | Applies            | Add 25 bps         |\\n| BB              | 160 bps              | 40 bps                 | 20 bps               | Applies            | Add 40 bps         |\\n| B               | 220 bps              | 55 bps                 | 25 bps               | Applies            | Add 60 bps         |\\n\\n## 3.3 Syndicated Loans - FAB as Mandated Lead Arranger\\n\\nWhere FAB acts as Mandated Lead Arranger (MLA) or Bookrunner on a syndicated transaction, the following additional floors apply on top of the standard term loan floors in Table 3.1:\\n\\n| Fee Component     | Minimum Floor                     | Notes                         |\\n|-------------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------------------|\\n| Arrangement Fee   | 30 bps of facility amount         | Payable upfront by borrower   |\\n| Underwriting Fee  | 15 bps of underwritten portion    | On retained exposure          |\\n| Participation Fee | 10 bps                            | On sold-down portions         |\\n| Agency Fee        | USD 25,000 / AED 90,000 per annum | If FAB acts as Facility Agent |\\n\\n## 4. Funds Transfer Pricing (FTP) Framework\\n\\nFAB operates a matched-maturity FTP framework under which each credit facility is assigned an internal cost of funds (FTP rate) corresponding to its contractual tenor and repricing frequency. FTP rates are set monthly by FAB Treasury and published internally by the 5th business day of each month."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "4.1",\n      "section": "4.1 FTP Rate Determination",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.032,\n      "text": "## 4.1 FTP Rate Determination\\n\\nThe FTP rate for each facility is determined as follows:\\n\\n1. Base Rate: The prevailing AED or relevant currency EIBOR (or applicable risk-free rate) for the matching tenor.\\n2. Liquidity Premium: An additional spread to reflect FAB\'s cost of term funding in excess of overnight rates, set quarterly by Treasury.\\n3. Tenor Premium: A further adjustment for facilities with tenors exceeding 3 years, reflecting FAB\'s increased balance sheet commitment.\\n\\n| Tenor Bucket   | EIBOR Tenor   | Liquidity Premium   | Tenor Premium   | Illustrative FTP (Jun 2024)   |\\n|----------------|---------------|---------------------|-----------------|-------------------------------|\\n| ≤ 3 months     | 3-month       | 15 bps              | 0 bps           | 5.25%                         |\\n| 3-12 months    | 6-month       | 20 bps              | 0 bps           | 5.40%                         |\\n| 1-3 years      | 12-month      | 30 bps              | 10 bps          | 5.55%                         |\\n| 3-5 years      | 12-month      | 35 bps              | 25 bps          | 5.85%                         |\\n| 5-7 years      | 12-month      | 40 bps              | 40 bps          | 6.05%                         |\\n| > 7 years      | 12-month      | 50 bps              | 60 bps          | 6.35%                         |\\n\\nIMPORTANT: FTP rates are indicative only. Relationship Managers must obtain confirmed FTP rates from Treasury at the time of term sheet issuance. Historical FTP rates are available on the Treasury pricing portal.\\n\\n## 5. Pricing Approval Authority Matrix\\n\\nAll credit pricing decisions must be approved at the appropriate level prior to issuance of a term sheet or credit sanction. The approval authority is determined by the combination of facility size, client credit rating, and the extent to which the proposed pricing deviates from the standard floor rates in Section 3.\\n\\n## 5.1 Standard Pricing - Within Floor Rates\\n\\n| Facility Size                | Client Rating   | Minimum Approval Authority            |\\n|------------------------------|-----------------|---------------------------------------|\\n| Up to AED 25 million         | All ratings     | Relationship Manager + Credit Analyst |\\n| AED 25M - 100M               | AAA to BBB      | Senior RM+Team Head                   |\\n| AED 25M - 100M               | BB and below    | Segment Credit Head                   |\\n| AED 100M - 500M              | AAA to BBB      | Segment Credit Head                   |\\n| AED 100M - 500M              | BB and below    | Regional Credit Committee (RCC)       |\\n| AED 500M - 1 billion         | All ratings     | Country Credit Committee (CCC)        |\\n| Above AED 1 billion          | All ratings     | Group Credit Committee (GCC)          |\\n| Any amount -Sovereign or GRE | All ratings     | Group Credit Committee (GCC)          |\\n\\n## 6. Pricing Exceptions\\n\\nA Pricing Exception applies when a proposed transaction is priced below the standard floors set out in Section 3, or where the calculated RAROC falls below the 13.5% hurdle rate. All Pricing Exceptions must be formally documented and approved before any term sheet is issued.\\n\\n## 6.1 Mandatory Documentation\\n\\nA Pricing Exception request must include the following:\\n\\n4. Full pricing model with all-in rate, RAROC calculation, and sensitivity analysis.\\n5. Written justification explaining the commercial rationale for the below-floor pricing.\\n6. Market evidence demonstrating that the proposed pricing is competitive.\\n7. Statement of relationship value, quantifying cross-sell revenues and total relationship RAROC.\\n8. Confirmation that the exception has been reviewed and endorsed by the Head of Credit Pricing.\\n\\n## 6.2 Approval Authority for Pricing Exceptions\\n\\n| Exception Type      | Max Deviation from Floor   | Approval Required              |\\n|---------------------|----------------------------|--------------------------------|\\n| Minor exception     | Up to 15 bps below floor   | Segment Credit Head            |\\n| Standard exception  | 15-40 bps below floor      | Country Credit Committee       |\\n| Major exception     | 40-80 bps below floor      | Group Credit Committee         |\\n| Strategic exception | Above 80 bps or RAROC < 8% | Chief Commercial Officer + CRO |\\n\\nWARNING: Any transaction that proceeds without the required Pricing Exception approval is a policy breach. Relationship Managers who execute transactions below floor without approval are subject to disciplinary action under FAB\'s HR Policy (HR-POL-DISC-001).\\n\\n## 7. Concentration and Exposure Limits\\n\\n## 7.1 Single Obligor Limits\\n\\nThe following single-obligor credit concentration limits apply to the aggregation of all credit facilities across all FAB entities for a single counterparty or group of connected counterparties:\\n\\n| Counterparty Type                          | Maximum Exposure                                  | Notes                                           |\\n|--------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|\\n| Non-bank corporate (Investment Grade)      | AED 3.5 billion                                   | Per group of connected counterparties           |\\n| Non-bank corporate (Sub- Investment Grade) | AED 1.2 billion                                   | Per group; requires GCC approval above AED 800M |\\n| Financial Institution (Investment Grade)   | AED 2.5 billion                                   | Interbank and trade lines combined              |\\n| Government Entity (GRE)                    | AED 5.0 billion                                   | UAE-domiciled GREs only; foreign GREs: AED 2.0B |\\n| Sovereign                                  | Country limit as approved by Board Risk Committee | Separate sovereign risk framework applies       |\\n| Real Estate Sector (combined)              | 25% of total corporate portfolio                  | Quarterly monitoring by Risk Management         |"\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Corporate_Term_Loan_Product_Manual_v2.0",\n      "clause": "3.1",\n      "section": "FIRST ABU DHABI BANK",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0315,\n      "text": "## FIRST ABU DHABI BANK\\n\\nCorporate Banking - Product Management\\n\\n## CORPORATE TERM LOAN - PRODUCT MANUAL\\n\\nProduct Structure, Eligibility, Pricing, and Term Sheet Standards\\n\\n| Document Reference   | FAB-PM-CTL-2024-v2.0                                    |\\n|----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Product              | Corporate Term Loan (AED and Foreign Currency)          |\\n| Effective Date       | 1 March 2024                                            |\\n| Owner                | Head of Corporate Lending Products                      |\\n| Target Segment       | Corporate clients with annual turnover > AED 50 million |\\n| Classification       | Internal -Relationship Manager Use Only                 |\\n\\n## 1. Product Overview\\n\\nFAB\'s Corporate Term Loan (CTL) is a bilateral lending product designed for corporate clients seeking mediumto-long-term financing for capital expenditure, project finance, acquisition finance, or general corporate purposes. The CTL is FAB\'s primary relationship lending product in the corporate segment and is the product type most frequently processed through the GERNAS Pricing Agent.\\n\\n## 1.1 Product Parameters\\n\\n| Parameter             | Specification                                                                                            |\\n|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Minimum Facility Size | AED 5,000,000 (or foreign currency equivalent)                                                           |\\n| Maximum Facility Size | Subject to single-obligor limits (FAB-CRP-CONC-2024-v1.8)                                                |\\n| Eligible Tenors       | 12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72, 84 months (standard); longer tenors require GCC approval                         |\\n| Eligible Currencies   | AED, USD, EUR, GBP, JPY, CNY (CNY subject to treasury availability)                                      |\\n| Interest Rate Type    | Floating (EIBOR/SOFR + spread) or fixed rate                                                             |\\n| Repayment Structure   | Bullet, amortising (equal instalments), or sculpted (cash flow linked)                                   |\\n| Security              | Unsecured (investment grade) or secured (see Section 3)                                                  |\\n| Eligible Purpose      | Capex, acquisition, working capital supplement, refinancing (not margin lending or speculative purposes) |\\n\\n## 2. Eligibility Criteria\\n\\n## 2.1 Client Eligibility\\n\\nThe Corporate Term Loan is available to clients that meet all of the following eligibility criteria:\\n\\n- Incorporated and operating entity with audited financial statements for a minimum of two years.\\n- Annual turnover exceeding AED 50 million (or foreign currency equivalent) as evidenced by audited accounts.\\n- FAB internal credit rating of B or above (CCC and below are not eligible without GCC waiver).\\n- Clean KYC status - no outstanding AML flags or sanctions screening alerts.\\n- Satisfactory credit bureau check with no material adverse information within the preceding 24 months.\\n\\n## 2.2 Excluded Purposes\\n\\nThe Corporate Term Loan may not be used for the following purposes:\\n\\n- Margin lending, trading in securities, or investment in mutual funds or hedge funds.\\n- Financing of activities prohibited under UAE law or FAB\'s Prohibited Sectors List (PSL-2024).\\n- Refinancing of existing FAB facilities at below-market pricing without proper exception approval.\\n\\n## 3. Pricing Structure\\n\\n## 3.1 Standard Pricing Components\\n\\nThe all-in pricing for a Corporate Term Loan comprises the following components, all of which must be included in the pricing model submitted for credit approval:\\n\\n| Pricing Component      | Typical Range                 | Description                                                                                                      |\\n|------------------------|-------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Base Rate (FTP)        | Set by Treasury monthly       | Matched-maturity internal cost of funds; AED EIBOR- based for AED facilities; SOFR-based for USD                 |\\n| Credit Spread (Margin) | 65-450 bps over FTP           | Risk-based spread reflecting client rating, security, and tenor; subject to floors in FAB-POL-PRICE-2024- v2.4   |\\n| Arrangement Fee        | 30-100 bps of facility amount | One-time fee payable at signing or first drawdown; included in RAROC calculation on annualised basis             |\\n| Commitment Fee         | 0-40 bps p.a. on undrawn      | Applicable to facilities with availability period > 30 days; standard commitment fee is 35% of applicable margin |\\n| Agency Fee             | USD 15,000 - 50,000 p.a.      | Applicable where FAB acts as Facility Agent in syndicated structures                                             |\\n\\n## 3.2 Pricing Floors - Reference to Credit Pricing Policy\\n\\nMinimum pricing floors applicable to all Corporate Term Loans are governed by FAB\'s Credit Pricing Policy (FABPOL-PRICE-2024-v2.4), Section 3.1. The GERNAS Pricing Agent will automatically retrieve applicable floors from the Knowledge Graph based on the client\'s credit rating, facility tenor, and currency. Relationship Managers must not override the floor without a documented Pricing Exception as per Section 6 of the Credit Pricing Policy.\\n\\nPRICING AGENT USERS: When using the GERNAS Pricing Agent for CTL pricing, input the following parameters to ensure correct floor retrieval: product\\\\_type = \'corporate\\\\_term\\\\_loan\', tenor\\\\_months = [actual months], currency = [AED/USD/etc], client\\\\_rating = [FAB internal rating]. The agent will retrieve the applicable floor from the Knowledge Graph and validate all scenarios against it."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "Section 6",\n      "section": "FIRST ABU DHABI BANK",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0303,\n      "text": "## FIRST ABU DHABI BANK\\n\\nCommercial Banking - Credit &amp; Pricing Division\\n\\n## CREDIT PRICING POLICY\\n\\nCorporate &amp; Commercial Banking - Lending Products\\n\\n| Document Reference   | FAB-POL-PRICE-2024-v2.4                     |\\n|----------------------|---------------------------------------------|\\n| Effective Date       | 1 June 2024                                 |\\n| Review Date          | 31 May 2025                                 |\\n| Approved By          | Chief Commercial Officer, FAB               |\\n| Owner                | Head of Credit Pricing, Commercial Banking  |\\n| Classification       | STRICTLY CONFIDENTIAL -Internal Use Only    |\\n| Replaces             | FAB-POL-PRICE-2023-v2.3 dated 15 March 2023 |\\n\\n## 1. Purpose and Scope\\n\\nThis policy establishes the minimum pricing standards, approval authority requirements, and governance controls applicable to all credit facilities extended by First Abu Dhabi Bank (FAB) under its Corporate and Commercial Banking franchise. It applies to all relationship managers, credit officers, and product teams involved in the origination, structuring, or repricing of credit facilities.\\n\\nThis policy is designed to ensure that all credit pricing decisions:\\n\\n- Recover FAB\'s fully loaded cost of funds, capital, and operational costs.\\n- Generate risk-adjusted returns commensurate with the credit risk assumed.\\n- Comply with applicable UAE Central Bank (CBUAE) regulations and FAB\'s own risk appetite.\\n- Are documented, approved at the appropriate authority level, and auditable.\\n\\nSCOPE: This policy applies to all corporate term loans, revolving credit facilities, syndicated loans, trade finance facilities, and treasury credit products originated through FAB\'s Corporate and Commercial Banking division. Retail lending is governed by a separate policy (FAB-POL-PRICE-RETAIL-2024).\\n\\n## 1.1 Definitions\\n\\n| Term                       | Definition                                                                                                                                                            |\\n|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Floor Rate                 | The minimum all-in pricing rate for a credit facility, below which no transaction may be executed without Pricing Exception approval.                                 |\\n| All-In Rate                | The total annualised yield to FAB from a facility, including margin, upfront fees (annualised), commitment fees, and any other recurring fee income.                  |\\n| FTP (Funds Transfer Price) | The internal cost of funds allocated to each facility based on tenor, currency, and product type, as determined by FAB\'s Treasury function on a monthly basis.        |\\n| RWA(Risk-Weighted Assets)  | The regulatory capital measure calculated by applying Basel III risk weights to the facility exposure, taking into account the counterparty\'s internal credit rating. |\\n| Capital Cost               | The annual cost of regulatory capital consumed by a facility, calculated as RWA × FAB\'s internal cost of equity hurdle rate.                                          |\\n| NIM (Net Interest Margin)  | The difference between the all-in facility rate and the applicable FTP rate, representing the gross spread earned by the business unit.                               |\\n| RAROC                      | Risk-Adjusted Return on Capital -the primary profitability metric used by FAB to evaluate credit transactions.                                                        |\\n| Relationship Value         | An adjustment to pricing that recognises the full revenue contribution of a client relationship across all products and services with FAB.                            |\\n\\n## 2. Pricing Principles\\n\\nAll credit pricing at FAB is based on four fundamental principles that must be satisfied simultaneously for a transaction to be approved:\\n\\n## 2.1 Cost Recovery\\n\\nEvery credit facility must, at a minimum, recover FAB\'s fully loaded cost of funds (FTP), allocated capital cost, operating cost allocation, and expected credit loss provision. A transaction priced below full cost recovery may only be approved under Section 6 (Pricing Exceptions) of this policy.\\n\\nThe minimum cost recovery calculation is:\\n\\n```\\nMinimum Rate = FTP Rate + Capital Cost (bps) + Operating Cost Allocation (bps) + Expected Credit Loss Provision (bps)\\n```\\n\\n## 2.2 Risk-Adjusted Profitability\\n\\nBeyond cost recovery, credit facilities must generate a RAROC that meets or exceeds FAB\'s minimum acceptable return on equity (RoE) hurdle, as set by Group Finance and reviewed annually. The current RoE hurdle is 13.5% post-tax.\\n\\n## RAROC is calculated as:\\n\\nRAROC = (All-In Revenue - Expected Losses - Operating Costs) / Regulatory Capital\\n\\nIMPORTANT: Transactions with RAROC below the 13.5% hurdle may still be approved if they meet the Relationship Value criteria in Section 2.4 below, subject to appropriate approval authority.\\n\\n## 2.3 Market Competitiveness\\n\\nPricing must reflect prevailing market conditions for comparable transactions. Relationship Managers are required to provide market evidence (peer bank indicative pricing, publicly available benchmarks, or Bloomberg comparable data) for all transactions above AED 25 million. The Credit Pricing Committee maintains a quarterly market pricing survey that serves as the primary benchmark for this requirement."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Corporate_Term_Loan_Product_Manual_v2.0",\n      "clause": "1.0",\n      "section": "4. Fee Schedule - Standard Terms",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0283,\n      "text": "## 4. Fee Schedule - Standard Terms\\n\\n| Fee                           | Standard Rate   | Floor Rate      | Notes                                               |\\n|-------------------------------|-----------------|-----------------|-----------------------------------------------------|\\n| Arrangement Fee-<AED50M       | 60 bps          | 30 bps          | Minimum subject to Pricing Exception if below floor |\\n| Arrangement Fee -AED50M- 250M | 50 bps          | 35 bps          | Payable at signing; non- refundable                 |\\n| Arrangement Fee ->AED250M     | 40 bps          | 30 bps          | Negotiable; GCC approval required below 35 bps      |\\n| Commitment Fee                | 35% of margin   | Min 20 bps p.a. | On undrawn portion during availability period       |\\n\\n| Prepayment Fee -Year 1    | 1.0% of prepaid amount   | Not waivable                                 | Protects FAB\'s funding cost hedges       |\\n|---------------------------|--------------------------|----------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|\\n| Prepayment Fee -Years 2-3 | 0.5% of prepaid amount   | Not waivable in Year 2; negotiable in Year 3 |                                          |\\n| Amendment Fee             | AED 25,000 flat          | Not waivable                                 | Per material amendment to facility terms |\\n\\n## 5. Documentation and Credit Approval\\n\\n## 5.1 Required Documentation for Credit Approval\\n\\n1. Completed Credit Application Form (CAF) - FAB-CAF-CORP-2024.\\n2. Audited financial statements - minimum 3 years; most recent year within 18 months.\\n3. Management accounts if audited accounts are older than 12 months.\\n4. Financing purpose documentation - project plans, acquisition agreements, capex schedules as applicable.\\n5. KYC documentation as per FAB\'s KYC Policy (FAB-POL-KYC-2024).\\n6. GERNAS Pricing Agent output - full recommendation with supporting scenarios, RAROC calculation, and MRM Evidence Pack.\\n7. Pricing Exception documentation if applicable (Section 6 of FAB-POL-PRICE-2024-v2.4).\\n\\nDOCUMENTATION NOTE: The GERNAS Pricing Agent MRM Evidence Pack (item 6 above) is a mandatory document for all credit approval submissions effective 1 June 2024. Credit proposals submitted without the MRM Evidence Pack will be returned without review."\n    }\n  ],\n  "total_results": 5,\n  "freshness_warning": false,\n  "latency_ms": 203.92\n}'}]}
2026-06-24 20:36:12,602 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=e9413d83644f3307bfd9a848836a661f span=9460ec2ba414fdb7 parent=- | {'role': 'assistant', 'parts': [{'type': 'text', 'content': 'Based on **FAB Credit Pricing Policy v2.4**, the minimum pricing floor for an **Internal Rating A** AED Corporate Term Loan is defined as a spread over the applicable AED Funds Transfer Pricing (FTP) rate. The exact floor depends on the facility tenor:\n\n| Facility Tenor | Minimum Pricing Floor (over AED FTP) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **≤ 1 Year** | **85 bps** |\n| **1–3 Years** | **105 bps** |\n| **3–5 Years** | **130 bps** |\n| **> 5 Years** | **165 bps** |\n\n**Key Policy Notes:**\n* **All-In Rate Floor:** The total all-in pricing rate must not fall below the matched-maturity AED FTP rate + the applicable floor spread above `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 3.1]`.\n* **Relationship Value Adjustment:** If the client generates documented cross-sell revenues exceeding **AED 500,000 per annum** across the relationship, the required margin floor may be reduced by up to **25 bps**, subject to relevant credit authority approval `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 2.4]`.\n* **Pricing Exceptions:** Any pricing proposed below these floors requires a formally documented Pricing Exception and approval at the appropriate authority level based on the deviation amount `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 6]`.\n\nFor the exact AED FTP rate to apply, Relationship Managers must obtain the prevailing rate from FAB Treasury at the time of term sheet issuance, as FTP is updated monthly `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 4.1]`.'}]}
2026-06-24 20:36:12,602 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=e9413d83644f3307bfd9a848836a661f span=ed10a1b5ac479ac9 parent=- | {'role': 'assistant', 'parts': [{'type': 'tool_call', 'id': 'x8p1s5945', 'name': 'search_documents', 'arguments': '{"query":"pricing floor minimum expected margin internal rating A AED term loan","top_k":10}'}]}
2026-06-24 20:36:12,602 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=e9413d83644f3307bfd9a848836a661f span=ed10a1b5ac479ac9 parent=- | {'role': 'tool', 'parts': [{'type': 'tool_call_response', 'id': 'x8p1s5945', 'response': '{\n  "results": [\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "2.4",\n      "section": "2.4 Relationship Value",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0328,\n      "text": "## 2.4 Relationship Value\\n\\nFAB recognises that relationship profitability extends beyond the individual transaction. A relationship-adjusted pricing approach applies where a client demonstrates a material cross-sell contribution, measured as total annual revenue across all FAB products divided by total RWA. Relationship Value adjustments may reduce the required margin by up to 25 basis points from the standard floor, subject to:\\n\\n- Documented cross-sell revenues exceeding AED 500,000 per annum across the relationship.\\n- Approval by the relevant credit authority (see Section 5).\\n- Annual review of continued cross-sell performance.\\n\\n## 3. Minimum Pricing Floors by Product\\n\\nThe following tables set out the minimum all-in pricing floors applicable to each product category. These floors represent the absolute minimum below which no transaction may be executed without a formal Pricing Exception (Section 6). Floors are stated in basis points over the applicable FTP rate unless otherwise specified.\\n\\nNOTE: FTP rates are published monthly by FAB Treasury and are available on the internal Treasury portal. All floor rates in this section are stated as SPREADS over FTP. The total all-in rate must not fall below FTP + the stated floor spread.\\n\\n## 3.1 Corporate Term Loans\\n\\nTable 3.1 sets out minimum pricing floors for standard corporate term loans, segmented by client internal credit rating and facility tenor.\\n\\n| Client Rating   | Tenor ≤ 1 Year                                        | Tenor 1-3 Years   | Tenor 3-5 Years   | Tenor > 5 Years   | Notes                                          |\\n|-----------------|-------------------------------------------------------|-------------------|-------------------|-------------------|------------------------------------------------|\\n| AAA / AA        | 65 bps                                                | 80 bps            | 100 bps           | 130 bps           | Investment grade sovereign or quasi- sovereign |\\n| A               | 85 bps                                                | 105 bps           | 130 bps           | 165 bps           | Strong investment grade corporate              |\\n| BBB             | 115 bps                                               | 145 bps           | 180 bps           | 220 bps           | Standard investment grade                      |\\n| BB              | 165 bps                                               | 210 bps           | 260 bps           | 320 bps           | Sub-investment grade / leveraged               |\\n| B               | 240 bps                                               | 300 bps           | 370 bps           | 450 bps           | Speculative / requires senior credit approval  |\\n| CCC and below   | Not permitted without Group Credit Committee approval |                   |                   |                   | See Section 6                                  |\\n\\nEXAMPLE: A BBB-rated client requesting a 4-year AED term loan. FTP for 4-year AED = 4.85% (as at June 2024). Minimum floor spread = 180 bps. Minimum all-in rate = 4.85% + 1.80% = 6.65%.\\n\\n## 3.2 Revolving Credit Facilities (RCFs)\\n\\nRevolving credit facilities are subject to the pricing floors in Table 3.2. Commitment fees on undrawn portions are in addition to the drawn margin and are not included in the floor calculations below.\\n\\n| Client Rating   | Drawn Margin Floor   | Commitment Fee Floor   | Facility Fee Floor   | Tenure ≤ 3 Years   | Tenure > 3 Years   |\\n|-----------------|----------------------|------------------------|----------------------|--------------------|--------------------|\\n| AAA / AA        | 60 bps               | 20 bps                 | 10 bps               | Applies            | Add 15 bps         |\\n| A               | 80 bps               | 25 bps                 | 12 bps               | Applies            | Add 20 bps         |\\n| BBB             | 110 bps              | 30 bps                 | 15 bps               | Applies            | Add 25 bps         |\\n| BB              | 160 bps              | 40 bps                 | 20 bps               | Applies            | Add 40 bps         |\\n| B               | 220 bps              | 55 bps                 | 25 bps               | Applies            | Add 60 bps         |\\n\\n## 3.3 Syndicated Loans - FAB as Mandated Lead Arranger\\n\\nWhere FAB acts as Mandated Lead Arranger (MLA) or Bookrunner on a syndicated transaction, the following additional floors apply on top of the standard term loan floors in Table 3.1:\\n\\n| Fee Component     | Minimum Floor                     | Notes                         |\\n|-------------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------------------|\\n| Arrangement Fee   | 30 bps of facility amount         | Payable upfront by borrower   |\\n| Underwriting Fee  | 15 bps of underwritten portion    | On retained exposure          |\\n| Participation Fee | 10 bps                            | On sold-down portions         |\\n| Agency Fee        | USD 25,000 / AED 90,000 per annum | If FAB acts as Facility Agent |\\n\\n## 4. Funds Transfer Pricing (FTP) Framework\\n\\nFAB operates a matched-maturity FTP framework under which each credit facility is assigned an internal cost of funds (FTP rate) corresponding to its contractual tenor and repricing frequency. FTP rates are set monthly by FAB Treasury and published internally by the 5th business day of each month."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "4.1",\n      "section": "4.1 FTP Rate Determination",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.032,\n      "text": "## 4.1 FTP Rate Determination\\n\\nThe FTP rate for each facility is determined as follows:\\n\\n1. Base Rate: The prevailing AED or relevant currency EIBOR (or applicable risk-free rate) for the matching tenor.\\n2. Liquidity Premium: An additional spread to reflect FAB\'s cost of term funding in excess of overnight rates, set quarterly by Treasury.\\n3. Tenor Premium: A further adjustment for facilities with tenors exceeding 3 years, reflecting FAB\'s increased balance sheet commitment.\\n\\n| Tenor Bucket   | EIBOR Tenor   | Liquidity Premium   | Tenor Premium   | Illustrative FTP (Jun 2024)   |\\n|----------------|---------------|---------------------|-----------------|-------------------------------|\\n| ≤ 3 months     | 3-month       | 15 bps              | 0 bps           | 5.25%                         |\\n| 3-12 months    | 6-month       | 20 bps              | 0 bps           | 5.40%                         |\\n| 1-3 years      | 12-month      | 30 bps              | 10 bps          | 5.55%                         |\\n| 3-5 years      | 12-month      | 35 bps              | 25 bps          | 5.85%                         |\\n| 5-7 years      | 12-month      | 40 bps              | 40 bps          | 6.05%                         |\\n| > 7 years      | 12-month      | 50 bps              | 60 bps          | 6.35%                         |\\n\\nIMPORTANT: FTP rates are indicative only. Relationship Managers must obtain confirmed FTP rates from Treasury at the time of term sheet issuance. Historical FTP rates are available on the Treasury pricing portal.\\n\\n## 5. Pricing Approval Authority Matrix\\n\\nAll credit pricing decisions must be approved at the appropriate level prior to issuance of a term sheet or credit sanction. The approval authority is determined by the combination of facility size, client credit rating, and the extent to which the proposed pricing deviates from the standard floor rates in Section 3.\\n\\n## 5.1 Standard Pricing - Within Floor Rates\\n\\n| Facility Size                | Client Rating   | Minimum Approval Authority            |\\n|------------------------------|-----------------|---------------------------------------|\\n| Up to AED 25 million         | All ratings     | Relationship Manager + Credit Analyst |\\n| AED 25M - 100M               | AAA to BBB      | Senior RM+Team Head                   |\\n| AED 25M - 100M               | BB and below    | Segment Credit Head                   |\\n| AED 100M - 500M              | AAA to BBB      | Segment Credit Head                   |\\n| AED 100M - 500M              | BB and below    | Regional Credit Committee (RCC)       |\\n| AED 500M - 1 billion         | All ratings     | Country Credit Committee (CCC)        |\\n| Above AED 1 billion          | All ratings     | Group Credit Committee (GCC)          |\\n| Any amount -Sovereign or GRE | All ratings     | Group Credit Committee (GCC)          |\\n\\n## 6. Pricing Exceptions\\n\\nA Pricing Exception applies when a proposed transaction is priced below the standard floors set out in Section 3, or where the calculated RAROC falls below the 13.5% hurdle rate. All Pricing Exceptions must be formally documented and approved before any term sheet is issued.\\n\\n## 6.1 Mandatory Documentation\\n\\nA Pricing Exception request must include the following:\\n\\n4. Full pricing model with all-in rate, RAROC calculation, and sensitivity analysis.\\n5. Written justification explaining the commercial rationale for the below-floor pricing.\\n6. Market evidence demonstrating that the proposed pricing is competitive.\\n7. Statement of relationship value, quantifying cross-sell revenues and total relationship RAROC.\\n8. Confirmation that the exception has been reviewed and endorsed by the Head of Credit Pricing.\\n\\n## 6.2 Approval Authority for Pricing Exceptions\\n\\n| Exception Type      | Max Deviation from Floor   | Approval Required              |\\n|---------------------|----------------------------|--------------------------------|\\n| Minor exception     | Up to 15 bps below floor   | Segment Credit Head            |\\n| Standard exception  | 15-40 bps below floor      | Country Credit Committee       |\\n| Major exception     | 40-80 bps below floor      | Group Credit Committee         |\\n| Strategic exception | Above 80 bps or RAROC < 8% | Chief Commercial Officer + CRO |\\n\\nWARNING: Any transaction that proceeds without the required Pricing Exception approval is a policy breach. Relationship Managers who execute transactions below floor without approval are subject to disciplinary action under FAB\'s HR Policy (HR-POL-DISC-001).\\n\\n## 7. Concentration and Exposure Limits\\n\\n## 7.1 Single Obligor Limits\\n\\nThe following single-obligor credit concentration limits apply to the aggregation of all credit facilities across all FAB entities for a single counterparty or group of connected counterparties:\\n\\n| Counterparty Type                          | Maximum Exposure                                  | Notes                                           |\\n|--------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|\\n| Non-bank corporate (Investment Grade)      | AED 3.5 billion                                   | Per group of connected counterparties           |\\n| Non-bank corporate (Sub- Investment Grade) | AED 1.2 billion                                   | Per group; requires GCC approval above AED 800M |\\n| Financial Institution (Investment Grade)   | AED 2.5 billion                                   | Interbank and trade lines combined              |\\n| Government Entity (GRE)                    | AED 5.0 billion                                   | UAE-domiciled GREs only; foreign GREs: AED 2.0B |\\n| Sovereign                                  | Country limit as approved by Board Risk Committee | Separate sovereign risk framework applies       |\\n| Real Estate Sector (combined)              | 25% of total corporate portfolio                  | Quarterly monitoring by Risk Management         |"\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Corporate_Term_Loan_Product_Manual_v2.0",\n      "clause": "3.1",\n      "section": "FIRST ABU DHABI BANK",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0315,\n      "text": "## FIRST ABU DHABI BANK\\n\\nCorporate Banking - Product Management\\n\\n## CORPORATE TERM LOAN - PRODUCT MANUAL\\n\\nProduct Structure, Eligibility, Pricing, and Term Sheet Standards\\n\\n| Document Reference   | FAB-PM-CTL-2024-v2.0                                    |\\n|----------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Product              | Corporate Term Loan (AED and Foreign Currency)          |\\n| Effective Date       | 1 March 2024                                            |\\n| Owner                | Head of Corporate Lending Products                      |\\n| Target Segment       | Corporate clients with annual turnover > AED 50 million |\\n| Classification       | Internal -Relationship Manager Use Only                 |\\n\\n## 1. Product Overview\\n\\nFAB\'s Corporate Term Loan (CTL) is a bilateral lending product designed for corporate clients seeking mediumto-long-term financing for capital expenditure, project finance, acquisition finance, or general corporate purposes. The CTL is FAB\'s primary relationship lending product in the corporate segment and is the product type most frequently processed through the GERNAS Pricing Agent.\\n\\n## 1.1 Product Parameters\\n\\n| Parameter             | Specification                                                                                            |\\n|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Minimum Facility Size | AED 5,000,000 (or foreign currency equivalent)                                                           |\\n| Maximum Facility Size | Subject to single-obligor limits (FAB-CRP-CONC-2024-v1.8)                                                |\\n| Eligible Tenors       | 12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72, 84 months (standard); longer tenors require GCC approval                         |\\n| Eligible Currencies   | AED, USD, EUR, GBP, JPY, CNY (CNY subject to treasury availability)                                      |\\n| Interest Rate Type    | Floating (EIBOR/SOFR + spread) or fixed rate                                                             |\\n| Repayment Structure   | Bullet, amortising (equal instalments), or sculpted (cash flow linked)                                   |\\n| Security              | Unsecured (investment grade) or secured (see Section 3)                                                  |\\n| Eligible Purpose      | Capex, acquisition, working capital supplement, refinancing (not margin lending or speculative purposes) |\\n\\n## 2. Eligibility Criteria\\n\\n## 2.1 Client Eligibility\\n\\nThe Corporate Term Loan is available to clients that meet all of the following eligibility criteria:\\n\\n- Incorporated and operating entity with audited financial statements for a minimum of two years.\\n- Annual turnover exceeding AED 50 million (or foreign currency equivalent) as evidenced by audited accounts.\\n- FAB internal credit rating of B or above (CCC and below are not eligible without GCC waiver).\\n- Clean KYC status - no outstanding AML flags or sanctions screening alerts.\\n- Satisfactory credit bureau check with no material adverse information within the preceding 24 months.\\n\\n## 2.2 Excluded Purposes\\n\\nThe Corporate Term Loan may not be used for the following purposes:\\n\\n- Margin lending, trading in securities, or investment in mutual funds or hedge funds.\\n- Financing of activities prohibited under UAE law or FAB\'s Prohibited Sectors List (PSL-2024).\\n- Refinancing of existing FAB facilities at below-market pricing without proper exception approval.\\n\\n## 3. Pricing Structure\\n\\n## 3.1 Standard Pricing Components\\n\\nThe all-in pricing for a Corporate Term Loan comprises the following components, all of which must be included in the pricing model submitted for credit approval:\\n\\n| Pricing Component      | Typical Range                 | Description                                                                                                      |\\n|------------------------|-------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Base Rate (FTP)        | Set by Treasury monthly       | Matched-maturity internal cost of funds; AED EIBOR- based for AED facilities; SOFR-based for USD                 |\\n| Credit Spread (Margin) | 65-450 bps over FTP           | Risk-based spread reflecting client rating, security, and tenor; subject to floors in FAB-POL-PRICE-2024- v2.4   |\\n| Arrangement Fee        | 30-100 bps of facility amount | One-time fee payable at signing or first drawdown; included in RAROC calculation on annualised basis             |\\n| Commitment Fee         | 0-40 bps p.a. on undrawn      | Applicable to facilities with availability period > 30 days; standard commitment fee is 35% of applicable margin |\\n| Agency Fee             | USD 15,000 - 50,000 p.a.      | Applicable where FAB acts as Facility Agent in syndicated structures                                             |\\n\\n## 3.2 Pricing Floors - Reference to Credit Pricing Policy\\n\\nMinimum pricing floors applicable to all Corporate Term Loans are governed by FAB\'s Credit Pricing Policy (FABPOL-PRICE-2024-v2.4), Section 3.1. The GERNAS Pricing Agent will automatically retrieve applicable floors from the Knowledge Graph based on the client\'s credit rating, facility tenor, and currency. Relationship Managers must not override the floor without a documented Pricing Exception as per Section 6 of the Credit Pricing Policy.\\n\\nPRICING AGENT USERS: When using the GERNAS Pricing Agent for CTL pricing, input the following parameters to ensure correct floor retrieval: product\\\\_type = \'corporate\\\\_term\\\\_loan\', tenor\\\\_months = [actual months], currency = [AED/USD/etc], client\\\\_rating = [FAB internal rating]. The agent will retrieve the applicable floor from the Knowledge Graph and validate all scenarios against it."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4",\n      "clause": "Section 6",\n      "section": "FIRST ABU DHABI BANK",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0303,\n      "text": "## FIRST ABU DHABI BANK\\n\\nCommercial Banking - Credit &amp; Pricing Division\\n\\n## CREDIT PRICING POLICY\\n\\nCorporate &amp; Commercial Banking - Lending Products\\n\\n| Document Reference   | FAB-POL-PRICE-2024-v2.4                     |\\n|----------------------|---------------------------------------------|\\n| Effective Date       | 1 June 2024                                 |\\n| Review Date          | 31 May 2025                                 |\\n| Approved By          | Chief Commercial Officer, FAB               |\\n| Owner                | Head of Credit Pricing, Commercial Banking  |\\n| Classification       | STRICTLY CONFIDENTIAL -Internal Use Only    |\\n| Replaces             | FAB-POL-PRICE-2023-v2.3 dated 15 March 2023 |\\n\\n## 1. Purpose and Scope\\n\\nThis policy establishes the minimum pricing standards, approval authority requirements, and governance controls applicable to all credit facilities extended by First Abu Dhabi Bank (FAB) under its Corporate and Commercial Banking franchise. It applies to all relationship managers, credit officers, and product teams involved in the origination, structuring, or repricing of credit facilities.\\n\\nThis policy is designed to ensure that all credit pricing decisions:\\n\\n- Recover FAB\'s fully loaded cost of funds, capital, and operational costs.\\n- Generate risk-adjusted returns commensurate with the credit risk assumed.\\n- Comply with applicable UAE Central Bank (CBUAE) regulations and FAB\'s own risk appetite.\\n- Are documented, approved at the appropriate authority level, and auditable.\\n\\nSCOPE: This policy applies to all corporate term loans, revolving credit facilities, syndicated loans, trade finance facilities, and treasury credit products originated through FAB\'s Corporate and Commercial Banking division. Retail lending is governed by a separate policy (FAB-POL-PRICE-RETAIL-2024).\\n\\n## 1.1 Definitions\\n\\n| Term                       | Definition                                                                                                                                                            |\\n|----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Floor Rate                 | The minimum all-in pricing rate for a credit facility, below which no transaction may be executed without Pricing Exception approval.                                 |\\n| All-In Rate                | The total annualised yield to FAB from a facility, including margin, upfront fees (annualised), commitment fees, and any other recurring fee income.                  |\\n| FTP (Funds Transfer Price) | The internal cost of funds allocated to each facility based on tenor, currency, and product type, as determined by FAB\'s Treasury function on a monthly basis.        |\\n| RWA(Risk-Weighted Assets)  | The regulatory capital measure calculated by applying Basel III risk weights to the facility exposure, taking into account the counterparty\'s internal credit rating. |\\n| Capital Cost               | The annual cost of regulatory capital consumed by a facility, calculated as RWA × FAB\'s internal cost of equity hurdle rate.                                          |\\n| NIM (Net Interest Margin)  | The difference between the all-in facility rate and the applicable FTP rate, representing the gross spread earned by the business unit.                               |\\n| RAROC                      | Risk-Adjusted Return on Capital -the primary profitability metric used by FAB to evaluate credit transactions.                                                        |\\n| Relationship Value         | An adjustment to pricing that recognises the full revenue contribution of a client relationship across all products and services with FAB.                            |\\n\\n## 2. Pricing Principles\\n\\nAll credit pricing at FAB is based on four fundamental principles that must be satisfied simultaneously for a transaction to be approved:\\n\\n## 2.1 Cost Recovery\\n\\nEvery credit facility must, at a minimum, recover FAB\'s fully loaded cost of funds (FTP), allocated capital cost, operating cost allocation, and expected credit loss provision. A transaction priced below full cost recovery may only be approved under Section 6 (Pricing Exceptions) of this policy.\\n\\nThe minimum cost recovery calculation is:\\n\\n```\\nMinimum Rate = FTP Rate + Capital Cost (bps) + Operating Cost Allocation (bps) + Expected Credit Loss Provision (bps)\\n```\\n\\n## 2.2 Risk-Adjusted Profitability\\n\\nBeyond cost recovery, credit facilities must generate a RAROC that meets or exceeds FAB\'s minimum acceptable return on equity (RoE) hurdle, as set by Group Finance and reviewed annually. The current RoE hurdle is 13.5% post-tax.\\n\\n## RAROC is calculated as:\\n\\nRAROC = (All-In Revenue - Expected Losses - Operating Costs) / Regulatory Capital\\n\\nIMPORTANT: Transactions with RAROC below the 13.5% hurdle may still be approved if they meet the Relationship Value criteria in Section 2.4 below, subject to appropriate approval authority.\\n\\n## 2.3 Market Competitiveness\\n\\nPricing must reflect prevailing market conditions for comparable transactions. Relationship Managers are required to provide market evidence (peer bank indicative pricing, publicly available benchmarks, or Bloomberg comparable data) for all transactions above AED 25 million. The Credit Pricing Committee maintains a quarterly market pricing survey that serves as the primary benchmark for this requirement."\n    },\n    {\n      "source": "FAB_Corporate_Term_Loan_Product_Manual_v2.0",\n      "clause": "1.0",\n      "section": "4. Fee Schedule - Standard Terms",\n      "effective_date": "",\n      "stale": false,\n      "score": 0.0283,\n      "text": "## 4. Fee Schedule - Standard Terms\\n\\n| Fee                           | Standard Rate   | Floor Rate      | Notes                                               |\\n|-------------------------------|-----------------|-----------------|-----------------------------------------------------|\\n| Arrangement Fee-<AED50M       | 60 bps          | 30 bps          | Minimum subject to Pricing Exception if below floor |\\n| Arrangement Fee -AED50M- 250M | 50 bps          | 35 bps          | Payable at signing; non- refundable                 |\\n| Arrangement Fee ->AED250M     | 40 bps          | 30 bps          | Negotiable; GCC approval required below 35 bps      |\\n| Commitment Fee                | 35% of margin   | Min 20 bps p.a. | On undrawn portion during availability period       |\\n\\n| Prepayment Fee -Year 1    | 1.0% of prepaid amount   | Not waivable                                 | Protects FAB\'s funding cost hedges       |\\n|---------------------------|--------------------------|----------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|\\n| Prepayment Fee -Years 2-3 | 0.5% of prepaid amount   | Not waivable in Year 2; negotiable in Year 3 |                                          |\\n| Amendment Fee             | AED 25,000 flat          | Not waivable                                 | Per material amendment to facility terms |\\n\\n## 5. Documentation and Credit Approval\\n\\n## 5.1 Required Documentation for Credit Approval\\n\\n1. Completed Credit Application Form (CAF) - FAB-CAF-CORP-2024.\\n2. Audited financial statements - minimum 3 years; most recent year within 18 months.\\n3. Management accounts if audited accounts are older than 12 months.\\n4. Financing purpose documentation - project plans, acquisition agreements, capex schedules as applicable.\\n5. KYC documentation as per FAB\'s KYC Policy (FAB-POL-KYC-2024).\\n6. GERNAS Pricing Agent output - full recommendation with supporting scenarios, RAROC calculation, and MRM Evidence Pack.\\n7. Pricing Exception documentation if applicable (Section 6 of FAB-POL-PRICE-2024-v2.4).\\n\\nDOCUMENTATION NOTE: The GERNAS Pricing Agent MRM Evidence Pack (item 6 above) is a mandatory document for all credit approval submissions effective 1 June 2024. Credit proposals submitted without the MRM Evidence Pack will be returned without review."\n    }\n  ],\n  "total_results": 5,\n  "freshness_warning": false,\n  "latency_ms": 203.92\n}'}]}
2026-06-24 20:36:12,603 | INFO     | agent_framework  | trace=e9413d83644f3307bfd9a848836a661f span=ed10a1b5ac479ac9 parent=- | {'role': 'assistant', 'parts': [{'type': 'text', 'content': 'Based on **FAB Credit Pricing Policy v2.4**, the minimum pricing floor for an **Internal Rating A** AED Corporate Term Loan is defined as a spread over the applicable AED Funds Transfer Pricing (FTP) rate. The exact floor depends on the facility tenor:\n\n| Facility Tenor | Minimum Pricing Floor (over AED FTP) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **≤ 1 Year** | **85 bps** |\n| **1–3 Years** | **105 bps** |\n| **3–5 Years** | **130 bps** |\n| **> 5 Years** | **165 bps** |\n\n**Key Policy Notes:**\n* **All-In Rate Floor:** The total all-in pricing rate must not fall below the matched-maturity AED FTP rate + the applicable floor spread above `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 3.1]`.\n* **Relationship Value Adjustment:** If the client generates documented cross-sell revenues exceeding **AED 500,000 per annum** across the relationship, the required margin floor may be reduced by up to **25 bps**, subject to relevant credit authority approval `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 2.4]`.\n* **Pricing Exceptions:** Any pricing proposed below these floors requires a formally documented Pricing Exception and approval at the appropriate authority level based on the deviation amount `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 6]`.\n\nFor the exact AED FTP rate to apply, Relationship Managers must obtain the prevailing rate from FAB Treasury at the time of term sheet issuance, as FTP is updated monthly `[FAB_Credit_Pricing_Policy_v2.4 · Section 4.1]`.'}]}
